file_metadata.title: Machine learning for hypothesis generation in biology and medicine: exploring the latent space of neuroscience and developmental bioelectricity

chunks.text: The scientific process relies on both rigorous hypothesis testing and the generation of insightful research directions.  The challenge lies in deriving novel hypotheses that transcend disciplinary boundaries, keeping pace with advances in data science and technology.  This requires identifying symmetries and patterns in research literature to unify observations and motivate new research programs.
chunks.chunk_summary: Effective scientific progress requires not only hypothesis testing but also the generation of insightful research directions that connect disparate fields.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Machine learning, particularly "robot scientist" platforms, offers potential for not only data processing and automation but also guiding research by suggesting next experiments.  This is particularly relevant in bioinformatics, where understanding organism-level form and function requires moving beyond molecular information, and in developmental biology.  While ensuring the factuality of AI output is important, equally crucial is the development of tools to assist with the creative process of hypothesis generation.
chunks.chunk_summary: Machine learning tools can assist scientists by automating data processing, suggesting experiments, and facilitating the creative process of hypothesis generation.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: A key gap in current AI tools is the lack of support for identifying deep commonalities between disparate functional datasets.  Tools are needed to translate scientists' meta-hypotheses into actionable research programs by mining published studies.  This is particularly relevant in the study of real-time physiology, which bridges neuroscience and developmental biology.
chunks.chunk_summary: AI tools are needed to bridge the gap between disparate datasets and facilitate cross-domain knowledge discovery, particularly in fields like physiology that connect neuroscience and developmental biology.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Neuroscience and developmental biology, while distinct fields, share underlying dynamics.  Neuroscience focuses on electrical signaling in neural networks driving behavior and cognition.  Developmental biology recognizes bioelectric signaling in all cell types as crucial for morphogenesis.  Recent advances in molecular understanding of developmental bioelectricity are blurring the lines between these disciplines.
chunks.topic: Intersection of Neuroscience and Developmental Biology
chunks.chunk_summary: Neuroscience and developmental biology, though traditionally separate, are linked by the role of bioelectric signaling in both neural function and morphogenesis.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The functional capabilities of brains may originate from ancient bioelectric networks used in bacterial biofilms and later exploited for metazoan morphogenesis.  This suggests shared algorithms for scaling cellular activity into larger competencies, such as morphogenesis and intelligent behavior.  This symmetry has implications for applying neuroscience paradigms to biomedicine, leveraging its understanding of multi-scale causality.
chunks.chunk_summary: The complex functions of brains may have evolved from ancient bioelectric networks used for morphogenesis, suggesting shared algorithms across scales and potential applications in biomedicine.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The proposed symmetry between cellular collectives in anatomical and behavioral spaces has been empirically tested but lacks tools for large-scale hypothesis derivation from existing literature.  It's been suggested that neuroscience papers can be read as developmental biology papers by pivoting problem spaces and timescales, but this requires an efficient implementation.
chunks.topic: Symmetry between Anatomical and Behavioral Spaces
chunks.chunk_summary: The analogy between cellular collectives in anatomical and behavioral spaces requires tools for large-scale hypothesis generation from existing literature, translating between neuroscience and developmental biology.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: FieldSHIFT, an in-context learning framework, translates neuroscience paper abstracts to developmental biology by replacing specific words and concepts.  This generates insightful results for expanding scientific intuition and identifying testable hypotheses.  A bioinformatics approach validates some predictions, revealing quantitative conservation of genes between morphogenesis and cognitive behavior.
chunks.chunk_summary: FieldSHIFT translates neuroscience abstracts to developmental biology, generating new hypotheses and revealing conserved genes between morphogenesis and cognitive behavior.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: FieldSHIFT uses a domain translation dataset and two AI language models: fine-tuned BART and GPT-4.  The dataset consists of neuroscience and developmental biology sentence pairs with associated concepts. Trained biologists built the dataset and evaluated model translations.  The approach is applicable to other domains beyond neuroscience and developmental biology.
chunks.chunk_summary: FieldSHIFT uses a curated dataset and two AI models (BART and GPT-4) to translate between neuroscience and developmental biology, with potential application to other domains.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The Levin Lab's decades-long practice of manually translating neuroscience to developmental biology by substituting concepts like "brain" to "body" provided the basis for the dataset.  70 such translation pairs were collected.  These concept pairs were used to construct translations ranging from single sentences to abstract-length paragraphs, sourced from various texts.
chunks.chunk_summary: The dataset was built upon manual translations of neuroscience to developmental biology concepts, creating pairs ranging from sentences to paragraphs.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The BART-based translator learns a mapping between text domains using positive (neuroscience to developmental biology) and negative (unchanged developmental biology) samples.  This reinforces correct translations and provides additional developmental biology examples.  Beam search and cross-entropy loss are used for training, with AdamW optimizer and specific hyperparameters.
chunks.chunk_summary: The BART model is trained using positive and negative examples to learn domain-specific mappings, utilizing beam search and cross-entropy loss for optimization.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The GPT-4-based translator uses in-context learning with provided concept mappings.  No weight updates are performed; inference is run with training examples in the prompt.  This leverages GPT-4's pre-training on vast text data, including neuroscience and developmental biology concepts, to generalize and translate new concepts.
chunks.chunk_summary: The GPT-4 model utilizes in-context learning with concept mappings, leveraging its pre-training to generalize and translate new concepts without weight updates.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Model validation involved searching for abstracts containing test concepts from the dataset.  For concepts without exact matches, closest matches were used.  Two biologists graded real and AI-generated abstracts for interestingness and new ideas.  The goal was to assess the quality of translations and provide a baseline for comparison.
chunks.chunk_summary: Model validation involved expert evaluation of real and AI-generated abstracts based on their interestingness and potential for new ideas.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The bioinformatics analysis involved extracting genes related to 'Developmental process' and 'Behavior' gene ontologies in various species.  The percentage of 'Behavior' genes within the 'Developmental process' set was calculated.  Overlap between other gene ontology pairs served as a control.  A one-sample T-test compared the distributions of genetic overlap.
chunks.chunk_summary: Bioinformatics analysis assessed the overlap between genes related to 'Developmental process' and 'Behavior' gene ontologies across different species.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Expert evaluation showed GPT-4 with self-critique generated good translations in over half the cases, significantly outperforming BART. While real abstracts were rated higher, GPT-4's scalability allows for rapid hypothesis generation.  Compute budget and human oversight become the main limitations, along with input diversity and GPT-4's knowledge of domain symmetries.
chunks.chunk_summary: GPT-4 outperformed BART in generating good translations, offering scalable hypothesis generation with limitations in compute, oversight, and input diversity.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Examples of translations showed BART and GPT-4 performed best with familiar terms.  Esoteric terms were often mistranslated or ignored.  GPT-4 demonstrated superior translation of concepts like "cortex" to "tissue organization", showcasing its ability to handle more complex mappings.
chunks.chunk_summary: Translation examples highlighted the models' strengths with familiar terms and GPT-4's superior handling of complex mappings like "cortex" to "tissue organization".
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The hypothesis of conserved molecular mechanisms between developmental bioelectricity and cognitive/behavioral phenomena was generated by FieldSHIFT and further supported by GPT-4.  Bioinformatics analysis revealed a significant overlap between genes implicated in 'Behavior' and 'Developmental process', increasing from Drosophila to humans, suggesting co-option of developmental genes for cognition.
chunks.chunk_summary: FieldSHIFT and GPT-4 generated and supported the hypothesis of conserved molecular mechanisms between development and behavior, confirmed by significant gene overlap in bioinformatics analysis.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: FieldSHIFT, implemented with a domain translation dataset and two ML approaches, demonstrated the effectiveness of automated hypothesis generation.  GPT-4's in-context learning outperformed BART, producing good translations in a significant portion of trials.  Future work may explore open-source LLMs and multimodal strategies for enhanced performance.
chunks.chunk_summary: FieldSHIFT, using GPT-4, effectively demonstrated automated hypothesis generation, with future potential in open-source LLMs and multimodal strategies.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The study supports the hypothesis of conserved algorithms and molecular mechanisms between body and behavior control.  FieldSHIFT facilitated exploration of symmetries between behavioral science and morphogenesis, leading to the hypothesis of conserved genes.  Bioinformatics data further supported this, suggesting new targets for morphogenetic assays.
chunks.chunk_summary: The study supports the hypothesis of conserved mechanisms between body and behavior control, with FieldSHIFT facilitating exploration and bioinformatics data providing further support.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: This work represents the beginning of AI-guided exploration of the "adjacent possible" around scientific papers.  By exploring conceptual symmetries, AI can generate novel hypotheses and dissolve interdisciplinary barriers.  These "virtual" papers, while not published traditionally, serve as a creative repository complementing existing literature.
chunks.chunk_summary: AI can explore the "adjacent possible" of scientific literature, generating novel hypotheses and bridging disciplines through "virtual" papers.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: Limitations include the limited number of manually curated papers and the need for experimental validation of generated hypotheses.  Future work will involve larger datasets, improved LLMs, and empirical testing of FieldSHIFT-generated hypotheses, including assessment of experimental feasibility compared to human-directed research.
chunks.section: Limitations of the study and next steps
chunks.chunk_summary: Limitations include dataset size and lack of experimental validation, with future work focusing on larger datasets, improved LLMs, and empirical hypothesis testing.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]

chunks.text: The observed overlap between genes involved in morphogenesis and behavior has implications for evolutionary and biomedical research.  FieldSHIFT's approach provides a method for generating testable hypotheses in developmental bioelectricity, relevant to birth defects, injury, and cancer.  Future work will integrate this workflow into machine science pipelines and test its creative products across diverse fields.
chunks.chunk_summary: The findings have implications for evolutionary and biomedical research, with future work focusing on integrating the workflow into machine science pipelines and testing its broader applicability.
chunks.authors: ["Cody Rasmussen-Ivey", "Joel Stremmel", "Leo Pio-Lopez", "Patrick McMillen", "Thomas O’Brien", "Michael Levin"]
